AGI -&nbsp;Maternity as a 'epiphany' that reveals the profound meaning of life, "makes your fragility" and "gives you true solidarity among women". In a long interview - 42 minutes - in Diletta Leotta, Giorgia Meloni returns to talk about the meaning that she had in her life the birth of her daughter Geneva. The occasion is the episode of 'Amateur Mamma', the format of Leotta, spread on Mother's Day.
&nbsp;
During the conversation between mothers, Meloni also tells some family anecdotes in which she sees details of the relationship with her daughter and what kind of mother she feels.
&nbsp;
"Cloudly there is a person who has been with me since Geneva was born to whom I entrust myself very much, and then there is the father. Grandparents a little less because his paternal grandparents live in Milan, it is difficult. My mom's here. Then a lot of friends, class moms - tells the premier -. I found so much solidarity among mothers. That is not just political adherence, I do not know what the mothers of the Geneva class vote, but they always do their best to help me. It's all right. And not because I am the President of the Council, they do it among themselves. They see my commitment, this is a very beautiful thing that maternity gives you. Maternity also gives you true solidarity among women."
&nbsp;
"I'm in the chat" of the class parents, says the premier, "comment, I say my, vote, when they put votes, when I can participate, I make my mom."
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Being a mother has changed me a lot. Absolutely improved. I believe that motherhood gives you some things that are extremely important in life: give value to time - argues -. Optimize time, because all the time I lose is especially time taken away from her. Then it gives you the ability to put your priorities in line in your life. Maternity gives you the highest possible form of love and the most dramatic fear possible, that of dying. And in doing this he puts everything else back in place: things that put you anxiety, when you become a mother you say 'Vabbe' you do'. She's fine and you say 'The rest I manage'. It helps you to have an awareness and courage in doing everything else that is extraordinary. So, yes, it's something that gave me so much stability, it hit me. I became more pragmatic, more realistic, more attentive to the things that make sense."
<br> &nbsp;"I am also a person who is never happy, with all the anxiety that this entails. I was also an anxious person unlike what might seem. No: anxiety now but completely on another world: all the rest good or bad you think 'Yes' a solution you can find'. I'm a woman forced to be strong," says Meloni. "Maternity -&nbsp; continues - brings out all your fragility and puts them in place. One of the elements in which motherhood completely changes the perspective of your life: In the end, you realize that you are no longer the centerpiece, which naturally becomes another person. It doesn't take anything from you, it gives you more value to yourself. I never was afraid to die, when I became a mother, I put the problem: I can't die. Happiness, all we build, is always in relation to others. In the movie 'Into the wild' when he is about to die writes 'Happiness has to be shared', happiness must be shared.
<br> To Leotta who asks for guilt for the time that work takes away from her daughter, the premier responds: "The senses of guilt don't handle them. The problem is that guilt is tremendously diseducative. Because you try to overcome your guilt by doing the only thing you don't have to do: abstaining. The guilt often prevents you from saying 'no' and is the most diseducative thing you can do with a son, I'm afraid."
&nbsp;
"I give me a few rules with Geneva. I have the rule that I try to put her to sleep, because she endures everything but when she has to go to sleep I have to be there. In fact, I take it when I have to go around and stay more than one night out. That's your moment if you take that away from her, she lives it like a betrayal," she says. "And another rule, trivial, which I gave myself is that at the recites you must be there. Here's the dance paper in Geneva. Do you know what day they planted it? The first day of the G7. The only thing in a year I couldn't move - he says -. It was hell and it will be hell."
<br> "If I had to give advice to mothers, I would say: When your gut says it, follow it, you know what it takes. The instinct must always be followed," he says. And Leotta asks if her daughter, seven years old, has the phone, answers: "Ginevra stands there with the tablet, the videos, Tik tok, like everyone in his generation. Sometimes he calls his friends at home, he asks me, "Mamma give me the phone." No, I don't give it to you. But don't stop them, they're all like that. It becomes difficult."
&nbsp;
After making sure that she will read 'The Lord of the Rings to the Child' when she will be the right age ("I read it at eleven years), she says of her daughter: "You have clear ideas, you look like me. She doesn't like me as a child, in the sense that I was a very dark and heavy child, and she's very sunny, light. She dances much more than me, and this is good."
&nbsp;
